Package com.google.mu.util.patternmatch

Class PatternMatchingCollector<T,​R>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.google.mu.util.patternmatch.PatternMatchingCollector<T,​R>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.stream.Collector<T,​java.util.List<T>,​R>
    public abstract class PatternMatchingCollector<T,​R>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.stream.Collector<T,​java.util.List<T>,​R>
    Utility class to do functional pattern-matching on a list or a stream of input elements.

    A PatternMatchingCollector object can both be used as a Collector for a stream, or as one of several possible patterns passed to the static match(java.util.List<T>, com.google.mu.util.patternmatch.PatternMatchingCollector<? super T, ? extends R>...) method. For example: Path path = match( pathComponents, exactly((parent, child) -> ...), exactly(directory -> ...));

    Since:
    5.3

      • matching

        @SafeVarargs
public static <T,​R> java.util.stream.Collector<T,​?,​R> matching​(PatternMatchingCollector<? super T,​? extends R>... patterns)
        Returns a Collector that will expand the input elements and transform them using the first from patterns that matches. If no pattern matches the input elements, IllegalArgumentException is thrown.

        For example if a string could be in the form of <resource_name> with no qualifier, or in the form of <project>.<resource_name> with project as the qualifier, or in the form of <project>.<location>.<resource_name>, with both project and location qualifiers, you can handle all 3 cases using: 

        
    Substring.first('.').repeatedly().split(string)
        .collect(
            matching(
                exactly(resourceName -> ...),
                exactly((project, resourceName) -> ...),
                exactly(((project, location, resourceName) -> ...))));

      • match

        @SafeVarargs
public static <T,​R> R match​(java.util.List<T> list,
                                  PatternMatchingCollector<? super T,​? extends R>... patterns)
        Expands the input elements in list and transforms them using the first from patterns that matches. If no pattern matches the input elements, IllegalArgumentException is thrown.

        For example, to switch among multiple possible cases: 

        
 match(
     list,
     exactly((a, b) -> ...),
     atLeast((a, b, c) -> ...),
     empty(() -> ...));
